column7: Hi, GX team - What are the difference between `context.create_expectation_suite()` vs `profiler.build_suit()` and `context.datadoc()` vs `validator.save_expectation_suite()`?
column97:
Hey <@U04RJ5CUP2S>!

`context.create_expectation_suite()` creates an empty expectation suite that you can later populate with expectations.

`profiler.build_suite()` executes a profiler against your data to build an expectation suite pre-populated with some basic expectations related to your data.

`context.build_data_docs()` builds your Data Docs (html reports on your data validations) from your previously executed validations.

`validator.save_expectation_suite()` saves the  expectation suite actively being build with your validator, so that you may later pass that suite into a checkpoint for validation.

column7: Hi all, I want to check to see if my date column contains today's date. If it it has it success if not failure. The column is allowed to have past dates. Does anyone know of a check for this without having to put in all past dates as criteria?

column7:
On using <https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/data_asset/|Data Assets>: Do I always need to use them in combination with `BatchRequest`s or is it possible to use a Data Asset definition without further specifying a `BatchRequest`?

I ran into the case where I pretty much can specify everything within my Data Asset (e.g. split by year & month). Why would I need to specify a BatchRequest for that case?
column97:
Hey <@U017PJTGC9W>! Thanks for reaching out.

Batch requests identify a specific set of data, which may include multiple assets, or may be a subset of a single asset, depending on configuration.

Your interaction with them depends on your workflow -- utilizing fluent datasources reduces the need to interact with batch requests, but they are still occasionally needed.

When working with block-config datasources, batch requests are generally required to identify that specific sub-or-superset of your data to be utilized .

column97:
Hi <@U03HL4LUP71> - since you're using S3 on Localstack with a specific local endpoint for your stores, you'll need to move away from using the S3StoreBackendDefaults and instead define the stores yourself in the config, similar to what you've done for data_docs_sites. Here's an example for <https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/guides/setup/configuring_metadata_stores/how_to_configure_an_expectation_store_in_amazon_s3#3-update-your-configuration-file-to-include-a-new-store-for-expectations-on-s3|Expectation Stores on S3>. You'll need to do the same for your other stores.

You may also run into issues using a forward slash in S3 bucket names, but I'm not familiar with whether Localstack supports that - AWS <https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/bucketnamingrules.html|seems to not>.

column7:
I have a question regarding Great Expectations and our PostgreSQL data source. I'm currently working on a project where I need to perform a join operation on the data.
I know Great Expectations supports various types of data sources, including PostgreSQL, but I couldn't find explicit documentation or examples on how to perform a join specifically. I've gone through the official documentation and searched online, but haven't found a definitive answer.
Could someone please confirm whether it's possible to perform join operations on a PostgreSQL data source using Great Expectations? If so, could you provide some guidance or point me to any relevant resources?
column97:
Hey <@U04SQTXGL80>, welcome to the world of GX! :tada: As specificated in the documentation, GX does not perform operations on the data, so the join is not a functionality of great_expectations. This library only checks the data quality.

column7:
Hi all! I am trying to add a custom field in our Data Doc Validation results that stands for `"Engineer who owns this data (Contact)": "<mailto:engineer@email.com|engineer@email.com>"`. Ideally this value would be found in the Data Docs, so non-technical data users know who to contact if they get a failed validation.

Does anyone know how I could configure thing? Would it be in the Batch Request, Validator, or Checkpoint?

For context I am working with Great Expectation in an AWS Databricks Notebook, and my Data Docs are written and stored in an S3 bucket.
column97:
Hey <@U04V7JB8HJS>! Thanks for reaching out.

We would actually look to set this in the Expectation Suite, as the suite represents the guarantee (expectations) for the data.
This can be done by accessing the suite and setting a meta note:

```suite = context.get_expectation_suite("expectation_suite_name")

suite.meta.update({"notes": "<your_note_here">})

context.save_expectation_suite(suite)```
When your docs are next built, that note will be included with that expectation suite.

column97:
Hey <@U053A3WD0HJ>! Thanks for reaching out.

Just to clarify, is your `great_expectations.yml` located at:

`/app/prefect-airbyte/great_expectations/great_expectations.yml`

or

`/app/great_expectations/great_expectations.yml` ?

This is the error that surfaces when there is no valid `great_expectations.yml` provided for some reason, e.g. no `great_expectations` directory where this code is being executed, the path to a directory isn't provided or there is no `great_expectations` directory located there, and a key is provided which precludes generating an InMemory context.

In this case, if your `great_expectations` directory is at `/app/prefect-airbyte/great_expectations`, I would try:

```context = gx.get_context(context_root_dir="/app/great_expectations/")```
Specifying `context_root_dir` is important here; pointing directly to the `yml`, or not providing the appropriate argument name, will prevent this from working.

column7:
Hello everyone,

I have a question regarding *custom expectations*. I have created one inside my `plugins_directory` defined as well in the *data context*, however my expectation function remains unknown when I called from a JSON file (`expectation suite`) . It only works when I called it implicitly inside my Python script with an Import. Is it normal ?

Thanks in advance.
column97:
Hey <@U055HGUMA01>! This is correct.

Currently, Custom Expectations within the plugins directory are only registered once:

1. Your context has been instantiated, and
2. You have imported the expectation.
If you are, for example, running a script which executes a checkpoint containing a custom expectation, you will still need to import that expectation within that script, to ensure that it is able to be run.

```import great_expectations as gx

context = gx.get_context()

from expectations.your_custom_expectation import ExpectThingToBe```

column7:
Hi everyone, my team is testing GX for our daily data production. I have a question about implementing customized metrics and expectations.
We want to evaluate
1. the correlation and mean absolute error between two columns, so ideally something like `expect_column_pair_values_correlation_to_be_between`and;
2. the percentage change/difference between the means/medians of two columns, so ideally something like `expect_column_pair_means_difference_to_be_between`.
However we are not sure if we shall use `ColumnAggregateMetricProvider` or `ColumnPairMapMetricProvider` , or we have to create metric provider and expectation family by ourselves.
Another simple way is to add new columns like columnA * columnB and use `column_mean` to get the correlation. But we want to avoid these cumbersome steps if possible.
column97: Hello, <@U05B3B3EQ9Y> — it looks like you are interested in Column-Pair Aggregate metrics; is this correct?  If so, we do not yet have “an easy” way to do it — you would have to follow the pattern used for `great_expectations/expectations/core/expect_column_kl_divergence_to_be_less_than.py` but implement the logic for two columns in the aggregate sense, such as in the existing single-column aggregate metrics.  It is on our roadmap to develop a ColumnPairAggregateMetricProvide, but I cannot give a timeline at this point.  In short, whenever a metric deals with a statistic over all rows, that would be “Aggregate”.  If the metric compares the value in a given row to some value, then it is “Map”.  If you need the result quickly, I believe that your idea about a new column that reflects the information from ColumnA and ColumnB combined — and use the ColumnMean metric/expectation then it is a very good approach.  I highly recommend that you explore it.  I hope that this helps a little bit.  Thank you very much, and thank you for using GX!

column7:
Hi, I am working with Custom Query Expectations and have many questions regarding them.
• QueryExpectations *must* have the following attributes set:         1. `domain_keys`: a tuple of the *keys* used to determine the domain of the            expectation         2. `success_keys`: a tuple of the *keys* used to determine the success of            the expectation.
column97:
Hey <@U0408PXU07R>! Thanks for reaching out. Bear with me; this is going to be a lot of text!

To your first bullet point, that is exactly correct; the metric specified under `metric_dependencies` is utilized to execute your query, the results of which are then made available to your `_validate` method.

To your second bullet, calling `run_diagnostics()` on that expectation will allow you to inspect the results:

```diagnostics = ExpectQueriedColumnValuesToExistInSecondTableColumn().run_diagnostics()

print([x for x in diagnostics["tests"]])
print([x for x in diagnostics["errors"]])```
To your third bullet, when you define `success_keys`,  the items in the tuple are the names of the parameters *which are available for you to use during the evaluation of your Custom Expectation*. Defining `success_keys` is what makes those specific parameters available. Likewise, `domain_keys` are utilized to help define the domain on which your expectation will operate, and specifying those keys makes those parameters available, while allowing for an explicit separation of their function relative to success keys. Take a look at <https://greatexpectations.io/blog/pass-custom-parameters-in-custom-expectations-and-optimize-your-gx-workflows|this blog post> detailing a bit more about these keys, and what can / should be passed here.

We then optionally set default values for these keys, allowing for default customization of your expectation reducing the amount of parameters that *need* to be provided at runtime. In the case of QueryExpectations, explicitly setting a default query here allows the expectation to be utilized with that default query, or *optionally* provide a different query.

By the time we get to the `_validate` method, *all* of our keys have been defined (either by default or at runtime), and are all available via `configuration` for reference within that method. The delineation between success & domain keys is necessary to both to help expectations be self-documenting, and to enable functionality within the actual metric computation running your query.

To your fourth bullet, that doc is correct. When utilizing Custom Expectations, they must be imported after instantiating your Data Context. Many users will create import methods for particular use-cases that can be called within their workflows to minimize overhead on making these imports.

column7: Could one batch request validates multiple data assets (eg multiple sql tables) together with one expectation suite?
column97:
Hey <@U05246K45C4>! Thanks for reaching out.

Typically, a batch request points to a single asset. When utilizing the OnboardingDataAssistant, it is possible to configure multi-batch requests that do what you're describing.

It's also possible to pass a list of Validations to a checkpoint, where each entry in the list is a paring of a batch request point to an asset, and an expectation suite to validate that asset. In this way, it is possible for a single Checkpoint to validate many assets against one or more expectation suites at once.

Hey folks,

I'm a newcomer to GX and the GX community. I'm currently exploring the use of Great Expectations for enforcing data quality and validation standards in our datalake.

I'm curious to know if GX can handle scenarios involving data partitioned in a multi-level folder hierarchy on Azure blob store, where each *path containing a file has its unique schema.* In this case, I want to *obtain the schema information* from a separate file and then utilize it to validate and perform various tests on the data file in terms of completeness, *schema checks*, data type etc.

For example:

The folder structure for the *data files* appears as follows:

/_TravelDestinations/continent=Europe/country=Italy/cuisine.parquet_
_/TravelDestinations/continent=SouthAmerica/country=Mexico/cuisine.parquet_
_/TravelDestinations/continent=Asia/country=India/cuisine.parquet_
_/TravelDestinations/continent=Asia/country=Japan/cuisine.parquet_

The folder structure for the *metadata/schema files* appears as follows:

_/TravelDestinations/continent=Europe/country=Italy/schema.parquet_
_/TravelDestinations/continent=SouthAmerica/country=Mexico/schema.parquet_
_/TravelDestinations/continent=Asia/country=India/schema.parquet_
_/TravelDestinations/continent=Asia/country=Japan/schema.parquet_


Here is an example of how the content of the data and schema files may look like:
column97:
Hi <@U05F19E18Q0>, if I had to work with this sample config I would do something like:

```# read a schema file using pandas
italian_schema_df = pd.read_parquet('/TravelDestinations/continent=Europe/country=Italy/schema.parquet')

# Extract the names form the schema file (gets Pizza, Pasta, etc. as a series), then convert to a list
italian_schema_items = italian_schema_df['name'].tolist()

# Import Great Expectations
import great_expectations as ge

# Setup the environment
context = gx.get_context()

validator = context.sources.pandas_default.read_parquet('/TravelDestinations/continent=Europe/country=Italy/cuisine.parquet')

# Add an expectation to the validator
validator.expect_table_columns_to_match_set(italian_schema_items)

# Validate your data and visualize the results
checkpoint = context.add_or_update_checkpoint(
    name="my_quickstart_checkpoint",
    validator=validator,
)

checkpoint_result = checkpoint.run()

context.view_validation_result(checkpoint_result)```
This will output a nice html file with a report that shows the results of checking the columns in the cuisine parquet file agains the names in the schema.

Ot course you could iterate over the structure to get this done over all datasets.

I hope it helps!

The following code should help you from instantiating a datasource through to getting a validator:

```import great_expectations as gx
context = gx.get_context(context_root_dir=<YOUR_ROOT_DIR>)

dataframe_datasource = context.sources.add_or_update_spark(
    name="my_spark_in_memory_datasource",
)

dataframe_asset = dataframe_datasource.add_dataframe_asset(
    name="my_asset",
    dataframe=<YOUR_SPARK_DF>,
)

batch_request = dataframe_asset.build_batch_request()

expectation_suite_name = "insert_your_expectation_suite_name_here"
context.add_or_update_expectation_suite(expectation_suite_name=expectation_suite_name)
validator = context.get_validator(
    batch_request=batch_request,
    expectation_suite_name=expectation_suite_name,
)```
We'll review this gap and address as needed. :bow:

column7: Hey all! Does GX Cloud support windows? I know the open source version is not available so just curious
column97:
Hi <@U05J1TY3G0J>, we don't officially support or test against Windows on GX Cloud,  though we do have users who successfully use GX Cloud on Windows machines.

Please let me know if you're interested in seeing a demo and talking through this a bit more and I'd be happy to find us a time.  Thanks!
